WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.350
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger. Today, we are&nbsp;
going to be looking at almost philosophical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.350 --> 00:00:22.710
aspects of what mathematics is really about.&nbsp;
It's a very interesting question, of course.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.710 --> 00:00:28.980
It touches base with philosophical or scientific&nbsp;
issues, and there are lots of different opinions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.980 --> 00:00:34.890
that are possible. But I'm going to be sort of&nbsp;
positioning things in a somewhat novel way, as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.890 --> 00:00:42.780
you'll see. There's a really essential dichotomy&nbsp;
or duality that manifests itself. So if you asked&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.780 --> 00:00:48.300
the ancient Greeks what mathematics was, they&nbsp;
would have probably said something like arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.300 --> 00:00:54.420
and geometry—at least when we're talking&nbsp;
about pure mathematics. Applied mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.420 --> 00:01:00.720
of course, also involves astronomy and other&nbsp;
subjects. But pure mathematics really rests on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:05.580
arithmetic and geometry. Later on, algebra would&nbsp;
also have been included in that general story.

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:10.560
Now, which of these is actually fundamental&nbsp;
has changed over the years. With the Cartesian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:16.890
Revolution, the emphasis shifted from geometry&nbsp;
as being sort of fundamental to more arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.890 --> 00:01:23.940
and that's really what most mathematicians these&nbsp;
days, I think, would lean towards—that arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:30.330
is really sort of the bottom of mathematics,&nbsp;
really resting ultimately on the framework of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:38.640
natural numbers, which we denote by "N" or "Nat."&nbsp;
But in the 20th century, a new direction appeared&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:45.690
when people were trying to create a framework for&nbsp;
modern analysis. They realized that things were a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:51.510
little bit difficult, and they ended up bringing&nbsp;
in philosophers and philosophical approaches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:58.320
which ultimately resulted in creating set&nbsp;
theory—this modern set theory—which ostensibly is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:05.130
some kind of framework for analysis. We are going&nbsp;
to critique this very strongly in future videos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.130 --> 00:02:08.820
but that was sort of the motivation&nbsp;
for this introduction of set theory&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:14.450
as a foundational framework for mathematics. In&nbsp;
that direction, people started asking, "Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:19.970
if we're going to use set theory to prop&nbsp;
up analysis"—they didn't say it that way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:24.980
of course, but that was really what was going&nbsp;
on—"then how about other parts of mathematics?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:31.190
Can we build arithmetic from set theory?" And then&nbsp;
they did come up with a scheme for doing this. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:35.210
by the end of the 20th century, we had this&nbsp;
idea that first we start with set theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:40.520
and then we create arithmetic, geometry,&nbsp;
algebra, analysis, and so on from that.

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:47.300
Here is this way of constructing natural numbers&nbsp;
from sets that goes back to John von Neumann,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:53.300
which we've talked about. So in this framework,&nbsp;
everything is a set, and the starting point is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:59.870
the empty set, which turns out to be what we&nbsp;
equate with the number zero. Then we create&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.870 --> 00:03:05.360
the number one by taking this empty set&nbsp;
and taking a set containing the empty set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:12.530
so it's really the set containing zero. The&nbsp;
number two—well, one way of describing it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.530 --> 00:03:19.070
that it's the set consisting of both 0 and&nbsp;
1. So here is 0, and here is 1, and that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.070 --> 00:03:27.380
combination is the number 2. Then the number 3 is&nbsp;
the set consisting of 0, 1, and 2. So there's 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:33.140
there's 1, and there's the 2 that we've just&nbsp;
created. So we get this inductive way of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:43.340
creating natural numbers using these ever-bigger&nbsp;
zoos of forests of sets within sets within sets.

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:49.880
If we ask something like, "What is 78,143&nbsp;
explicitly in the system?" Well, then we have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:54.590
very big headache. If we had to actually stare at&nbsp;
that thing and write it down, or even just stare&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.590 --> 00:04:00.800
at it in terms of these brackets, it would be a&nbsp;
very big headache. But aside from being rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:07.460
unwieldy and, I think to most people, unnatural,&nbsp;
this set-theoretical approach to natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.460 --> 00:04:14.780
also has some theoretical challenges. In&nbsp;
particular, how are we going to define&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:21.380
the operations of addition and multiplication&nbsp;
on natural numbers when we view them in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.380 --> 00:04:30.270
very complicated set-theoretical fashion? And how&nbsp;
are we going to prove the laws of arithmetic from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:37.410
those definitions? Now, it is supposed by most&nbsp;
practicing mathematicians that this has been done&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:42.690
somewhere, somewhere over the hill. Some logicians&nbsp;
have done this, and we don't have to worry about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:50.790
it—that the laws of arithmetic are just God-given&nbsp;
to us by the logicians. It's an unhappy state of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:56.850
affairs. So it means that modern students aren't&nbsp;
actually exposed to seeing the arguments in front&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.850 --> 00:05:01.530
of them. We're not talking about something&nbsp;
that's very tangential or oblique, right?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.530 --> 00:05:08.430
This is a core issue in mathematics: how are we&nbsp;
going to set up arithmetic with natural numbers?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.430 --> 00:05:13.350
If we're going to do it in such a convoluted&nbsp;
way that we can only sort of point to these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:19.440
indirect references to things that are somewhere&nbsp;
else, it's a very unhappy state of affairs.

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:30.510
The 20th-century thinking has been very&nbsp;
disappointing, really. There's this whole sequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:38.190
of wrong thinkings that have been introduced&nbsp;
in this general direction. We have this idea&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:45.060
that math is based on sets, that everything&nbsp;
is a set. The definition of a set itself is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:51.600
finessed by the use of axioms. We really ought&nbsp;
to define what a set is properly if we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:57.480
to base everything on sets, but that's too hard,&nbsp;
and so we just assume that we know what a set is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:06.810
and invoke axioms to conjure up the things that&nbsp;
really ought to be theorems. The foundations of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:15.480
arithmetic then become subservient to unwieldy and&nbsp;
overly complicated set-theoretic arguments. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:26.280
naturalness of arithmetic is lost. We're giving up&nbsp;
our arithmetic to the set theorists, and in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:31.350
no one really uses the proofs critically. When I&nbsp;
say "no one," I mean practicing mathematicians,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:38.340
students at universities, people who&nbsp;
actually use the mathematics. To them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.340 --> 00:06:48.390
these proofs are essentially non-existent;&nbsp;
they're invisible. And I think it's a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:52.710
unhappy state of affairs. We're talking about&nbsp;
arithmetic, after all, right? We ought to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.710 --> 00:07:02.400
able to lay out arithmetic in a more sensible&nbsp;
and more publicly verifiable way than this.

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:08.640
So I'm going to be advocating a very&nbsp;
different approach to arithmetic in how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:15.300
we set up arithmetic, very different from the&nbsp;
20th century's point of view. The advantage&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:20.790
with our approach to arithmetic is that, first&nbsp;
of all, we are going to be flexible about which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.790 --> 00:07:29.400
data structures are suitable. We don't just have&nbsp;
sets at our disposal; we have lists, ordered sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:35.400
multisets, as well as sets. And we have now&nbsp;
some experience being able to judge that maybe,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:40.860
in certain situations, one of these is better&nbsp;
than another. So we have a flexibility that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:49.380
the set theorists don't. This gives us a big&nbsp;
advantage. Our definitions are going to be clear,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.380 --> 00:07:56.280
and they're going to relate directly to common&nbsp;
usage and intuition. We want an ordinary person&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.280 --> 00:08:01.290
to be able to look at our definition and say,&nbsp;
"Yeah, that kind of corresponds to the way we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:05.820
think about things," especially when we're talking&nbsp;
about natural numbers and their arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:12.630
for heaven's sake! All right, the theoretical&nbsp;
manifestation of the subject ought to correlate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:20.730
with the way people actually do arithmetic—that's&nbsp;
not asking that much. Our proofs are going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:27.180
make sense; they're going to be visible. We&nbsp;
can actually explain them to non-experts. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:33.000
don't have to pretend that we need all kinds of&nbsp;
prior logical training in order to be able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:41.490
deal with the complexity of these proofs.&nbsp;
And we're going to see that the doors are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:47.730
open to further insights into adjacent fields.&nbsp;
Once we understand arithmetic in a better way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:55.910
a lot of other adjacent things are just going to&nbsp;
be more accessible to us. And we're going to stick&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.910 --> 00:09:01.430
to reality, okay? And avoid wishful thinking. Just&nbsp;
because we want something to be true doesn't mean&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:06.440
that we're going to force it into our theory.&nbsp;
We're going to let nature decide what is true.

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:13.670
All right, so here is our main definition—the key&nbsp;
definition of what a natural number is: a natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.670 --> 00:09:27.320
number is an M-set or multiset of marks, marks&nbsp;
on a page. So, for example, this thing here—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:34.760
an M-set, as you can see by the brackets on the&nbsp;
outside—and it contains a mark, and another mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:43.310
and another mark. So these vertical strokes or&nbsp;
marks are going to be the things inside our M-set.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:48.110
There's only going to be one kind of thing in&nbsp;
these M-sets; they're always going to be the same,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.110 --> 00:09:55.280
these vertical strokes or marks. So that's what&nbsp;
we would ordinarily call the number three. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.280 --> 00:10:01.820
going to be our official designation, our physical&nbsp;
specification of what we informally call the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:12.800
number three. The number seventeen—that's what it&nbsp;
looks like officially; it's a multiset consisting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:20.570
of a lot of strokes. And there is a stroke,&nbsp;
or a mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.570 --> 00:10:29.060
mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark—that's&nbsp;
going to be our number seventeen. And notably,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:33.560
because we're talking about M-sets, we're&nbsp;
going to allow the possibility that there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:39.920
are no marks inside our M-set, that it's an empty&nbsp;
M-set, and that's going to be our number zero.

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:46.160
So, as opposed to previous usage,&nbsp;
with this approach to natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:50.450
we are going to include zero as a natural&nbsp;
number. This is a big difference from what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:56.660
we've been doing throughout this series up till&nbsp;
now. The series has always taken the point of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:56.660 --> 00:11:02.510
view that the natural numbers begin with one. But&nbsp;
when we adopt this multiset point of view, it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.510 --> 00:11:09.770
more natural to include the empty multiset as a&nbsp;
possibility, and so we have a natural number zero.

00:11:09.770 --> 00:11:19.310
Okay, that's all well and good, but there's still&nbsp;
this question: what exactly is a mark? Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.310 --> 00:11:23.660
so it's something that we're writing&nbsp;
down on the page. It's a symbol,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.660 --> 00:11:29.240
and it looks kind of like a 1, but I'm trying&nbsp;
to make it a little bit longer than a 1 so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:33.860
that we distinguish it a little bit from&nbsp;
the number 1. But what does it actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:44.630
represent? So the answer involves going deeper.&nbsp;
I claim that the natural numbers are not at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:48.830
bottom of things—that's usually the point of&nbsp;
view towards modern mathematics—that there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.830 --> 00:11:55.640
actually something else underneath the natural&nbsp;
numbers. And I'm now going to reveal what that is:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:55.640 --> 00:12:06.500
there's something even more fundamental,&nbsp;
essential, basic than our number system.

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:15.650
All right, so what is this essential dichotomy&nbsp;
or duality underlying mathematics? It's revealed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:23.090
here in this slide, which arguably&nbsp;
might be the single most important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.090 --> 00:12:32.810
slide in all of my videos. What do we&nbsp;
see? Well, we see on this side nothing;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:32.810 --> 00:12:43.610
nothing. On this side, something. There's a&nbsp;
difference—the difference between nothing and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:43.610 --> 00:12:51.950
something. I claim that this simple-minded&nbsp;
notice is really the central core dichotomy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:59.180
or duality underlying mathematics—the&nbsp;
distinction between nothing and something.

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:05.720
So this mark or stroke that we're representing&nbsp;
here, this basic symbol that we're using,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:05.720 --> 00:13:11.390
is the ingredient for our natural numbers.&nbsp;
This is our representation of something;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:17.960
it's a symbol that we introduce, which&nbsp;
represents this intuitive idea of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:25.520
thing. So we are definitely accessing our&nbsp;
intuition here; we're not giving definitions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:30.860
of something or definitions of nothing. If we&nbsp;
did that, we would go in philosophical circles;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:35.300
we could do that for years and years, talking&nbsp;
about what does nothing mean, what does something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.300 --> 00:13:43.010
mean. Okay, I just want to base things on our&nbsp;
intuitive understanding of those terms. We all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.010 --> 00:13:52.190
have an intuitive understanding of those terms and&nbsp;
represent the something by this symbol. There are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.190 --> 00:13:57.740
other possible symbols that we could have used and&nbsp;
that we could use. So we've used this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:57.740 --> 00:14:03.440
but maybe somebody else might be more comfortable&nbsp;
with a small circle, or a star, or maybe a slanted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:10.040
line, or maybe even a dot. Those would&nbsp;
be alternative, completely valid ways of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:10.040 --> 00:14:15.800
representing something. We could, of course, have&nbsp;
other symbols as well, but the point is we're just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:23.540
choosing one particular symbol, and that symbol&nbsp;
represents this primordial idea of something.

00:14:23.540 --> 00:14:31.220
And nothing—well, there's no choice about how&nbsp;
to represent that. There may be a lot of choices&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:36.320
about how to represent something, but there's no&nbsp;
choice about how to represent nothing. It's always&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:42.530
represented in the same way—by emptiness. You&nbsp;
leave the page empty; you don't put anything on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.530 --> 00:14:51.920
it. That is nothing, in our view. That's how we're&nbsp;
representing nothing on the page; it's just empty.

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:59.270
So although we've given a general definition&nbsp;
of natural numbers as M-sets of marks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:59.270 --> 00:15:07.460
we still want to construct them, okay?&nbsp;
We want to create them, put them on a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.460 --> 00:15:13.910
page, and demonstrate what it is that we're&nbsp;
talking about explicitly. And we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.910 --> 00:15:20.930
do this inductively, which means one step at a&nbsp;
time. I'm going to start with our empty M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:27.770
which is the simplest possible situation. It's&nbsp;
the empty M-set, which has nothing inside it;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:27.770 --> 00:15:36.030
it contains nothing. And we're going to give&nbsp;
it a name. We're going to call it zero because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:36.030 --> 00:15:43.620
that's the traditional word that we use for&nbsp;
that particular number, and we'll often write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:43.620 --> 00:15:51.180
it as a separate symbol with this sort of "o"-type&nbsp;
number symbol. So zero is, by definition for us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:51.180 --> 00:15:58.410
this M-set here. So, in fact, this symbol here&nbsp;
is extraneous; we don't actually really need it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.410 --> 00:16:04.260
It's logically unnecessary; we could use just&nbsp;
this thing here instead of zero everywhere. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:11.100
we prefer to connect with ordinary experience&nbsp;
and just then think about the usual zero as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:19.140
being actually, officially, this empty M-set.&nbsp;
So for us, this is the first natural number;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.140 --> 00:16:28.020
it's the first one that we actually explicitly&nbsp;
write down. Our first natural number is zero.

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:34.170
And now we can construct more natural&nbsp;
numbers, and the idea is always the same:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:38.280
we're going to take what we have, and&nbsp;
we're going to add something to it;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:49.770
we're going to insert something. So the next one&nbsp;
is this one here—the set or M-set consisting of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:57.030
something. It's an M-set with a single mark in&nbsp;
it. So make a mark, you put it in the M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.030 --> 00:17:07.200
and that we can say is the number one. And then we&nbsp;
can take this one and insert another mark beside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:13.410
it, so we have mark, mark. That M-set is two.&nbsp;
Mark, mark, mark—that's the M-set three. Mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:18.090
mark, mark, mark—that's the M-set four. Mark,&nbsp;
mark, mark, mark, mark—that's the M-set five.

00:17:18.090 --> 00:17:26.940
Notice, first of all, how much simpler this&nbsp;
construction of natural numbers is than the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.940 --> 00:17:31.890
set-theoretical one. Okay, notice that&nbsp;
it's actually a natural progression that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:31.890 --> 00:17:38.550
actually mirrors ordinary usage. Primitive&nbsp;
peoples would have written number five in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:38.550 --> 00:17:44.100
very much this way—a bunch of five&nbsp;
marks on a page, a piece of papyrus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:50.120
or something. This is very natural. The only&nbsp;
thing that's a little bit sophisticated,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.120 --> 00:17:55.670
that they wouldn't have done, is putting&nbsp;
everything in a pair of brackets to enclose it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:55.670 --> 00:18:02.240
to make the boundary very clear that the natural&nbsp;
number doesn't extend out here or out here.

00:18:02.240 --> 00:18:09.110
So these natural numbers are so&nbsp;
constructed in order. We see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:13.820
it's not just that we have a whole bunch of&nbsp;
natural numbers; rather, we start with zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:13.820 --> 00:18:20.150
and then we start to sequentially construct&nbsp;
more and more. There's a natural order:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:20.150 --> 00:18:24.380
after zero, then we have this one, and then&nbsp;
we have this one, and then we have this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:24.380 --> 00:18:27.830
and then we have this one, and then we have&nbsp;
this one, and so on. And we can keep going,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:38.420
at least until our patience or our resources run&nbsp;
out. So this is very explicit, very concrete,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:44.090
and now there's no more question about whether we&nbsp;
have a natural number or not. So from this point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:53.030
of view, you have a natural number precisely when&nbsp;
you can actually write down a multiset of marks.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.030 --> 00:18:59.510
If you can do that, then that's a natural number.&nbsp;
And if you can't do it, well, then you don't have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.510 --> 00:19:08.180
such a natural number. It's a very explicit way of&nbsp;
pinning down arithmetic to something concrete and,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:18.500
in fact, very close to our experience. So this&nbsp;
is going to, I think, be a good foundation for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:22.310
arithmetic. There's a very good foundation&nbsp;
for everything to take. But notice that it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.310 --> 00:19:27.410
exploiting our understanding of multisets. If we&nbsp;
